  "help": "Help",
  "helpTitle": "Help & guide",
  "helpIntro": "A practical guide to every part of VPS Admin. Tap a section to expand it. All text and commands can be selected and copied — long-press to start a selection.",

  "helpServersTitle": "Servers — adding & connecting",
  "helpServersBody": "The «Servers» tab is your list of VPS profiles. The highlighted (active) server is the one every other tab works with.\n\nAdd a server:\n1. Tap «Add VPS».\n2. Name — any label, e.g. «Oracle prod» or «Home NAS».\n3. Host — the server's IP (e.g. 203.0.113.10) or domain (e.g. vps.example.com).\n4. Port — the SSH port, 22 by default; change only if your server uses a custom one.\n5. User — the Linux account you log in as: root, ubuntu, admin…\n6. Start directory — the folder the Files tab opens first (e.g. /home/ubuntu).\n7. Folder — optional; groups servers under a heading so a long list stays tidy.\n8. Authentication — Password or SSH key (see the «SSH keys» section).\n9. Save.\n\nConnect:\n• Tap a server to make it active.\n• Tap the link icon in the top bar to connect. It is green when connected, grey when not, and spins while connecting.\n• If a connection fails, the reason shows at the bottom (wrong host/port, refused auth, timeout…).\n\nManage: tap the pencil to edit, the trash icon to delete. Deleting a server also removes its stored secret. Use the search box to filter a long list by name or host.",

  "helpSshTitle": "SSH keys — how and where to get them",
  "helpSshBody": "VPS Admin can log in two ways. Choose one per server in the «Authentication» field.\n\n1) Password\nThe simplest: enter the server's login password. Less secure (passwords can be guessed/brute-forced) and many cloud servers disable password login by default.\n\n2) SSH key (recommended)\nA key pair: a PRIVATE key that stays on your phone and a PUBLIC key that lives on the server. You paste the private key into the app.\n\nWhere to get a key:\n• From a cloud provider. When you create an instance (Oracle Cloud, AWS, Hetzner, DigitalOcean…) you are offered a private key to download — a file like id_rsa, id_ed25519, or something.pem / .key. Open it in a text editor and copy everything.\n• Generate your own on a computer (Linux/macOS, or Windows with OpenSSH):\n      ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C \"vps-admin\"\n  Press Enter for the default location and optionally set a passphrase. You get two files:\n      ~/.ssh/id_ed25519       ← private key (goes into the app)\n      ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub   ← public key (goes on the server)\n\nPut the PUBLIC key on the server (once per server):\n• Easiest, if you can already log in:\n      ssh-copy-id user@host\n• Manually: append the single line from id_ed25519.pub to ~/.ssh/authorized_keys on the server. If needed, create the folder and file with the right modes:\n      mkdir -p ~/.ssh && chmod 700 ~/.ssh\n      chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys\n\nIn the app:\n1. Set Authentication to «SSH key».\n2. Open «Private key (PEM)» and paste the FULL private key, including the first and last lines:\n      -----BEGIN OPENSSH PRIVATE KEY-----\n      …\n      -----END OPENSSH PRIVATE KEY-----\n   (older keys may say RSA PRIVATE KEY — that is fine too).\n3. If the key has a passphrase, enter it in «Key passphrase».\n4. Save, then connect.\n\nTroubleshooting:\n• «Permission denied (publickey)» — the public key is not in the server's authorized_keys, or you are using the wrong user. Re-check both.\n• Make sure you pasted the PRIVATE key (the long file), not the .pub one.\n• A wrong passphrase also shows up as an auth failure.\n\nThe key is stored only in the Android Keystore and never leaves your device or goes into git.",

  "helpInfoTitle": "Info — live server metrics",
  "helpInfoBody": "A read-only dashboard for the active server. It runs standard Linux commands over SSH and shows the results as cards:\n\n• System — hostname, OS and kernel version (uname).\n• Uptime & load — how long the server has run and the 1/5/15-minute load average.\n• Memory — RAM and swap usage (free -h).\n• Disk — space used and free per filesystem (df -h).\n• Top processes (CPU) — the heaviest processes right now.\n• Docker — running containers (docker ps), if Docker is installed.\n\nTap Refresh to re-run every check. The tab needs an active SSH connection — if you see a «Connect» prompt, connect on the Servers tab first.\n\nWhat to look for: a load average higher than the number of CPU cores means the server is busy; a disk over ~90% full, or RAM fully used with heavy swap, usually explains slowness.",

  "helpTerminalTitle": "Terminal — full SSH shell",
  "helpTerminalBody": "A real interactive shell on the server, the same as ssh from a desktop. Run any command, edit files with nano/vim, watch logs, and so on.\n\nUsing it on a touch screen:\n• The helper key row above the keyboard adds keys that are hard to reach: Tab (autocomplete), Ctrl (e.g. Ctrl+C to stop a command, Ctrl+D to log out), Esc and arrow keys.\n• Paste inserts text from the clipboard — handy for long commands.\n• Clear wipes the screen (like the clear command).\n• Output scrolls; swipe up to review earlier lines.\n\nThe terminal needs an active connection. If the session drops (network change, timeout), tap «Try again» to reopen the shell. Each connect starts a fresh shell, so a previous session's foreground work is gone.\n\nTip: for long-running tasks use tmux or screen on the server, so the work survives a disconnect and you can re-attach later.",

  "helpFilesTitle": "Files — SFTP browser & editor",
  "helpFilesBody": "Browse, open and edit files on the server over SFTP (secure file transfer over SSH).\n\nNavigation:\n• Tap a folder to enter it; tap «Up» to go to the parent.\n• The current path is shown at the top.\n• The list starts in the server's Start directory.\n\nEditing:\n• Tap a text file (config, script, .env, log…) to open it in the built-in editor.\n• Make changes and tap Save to write it back to the server.\n• The editor shows the line count and a «modified» marker for unsaved changes, and warns before you leave with changes unsaved.\n\nLimits:\n• Binary files (images, archives, executables) are not opened in the editor.\n• Very large files are blocked to keep the editor responsive — edit those in the Terminal with nano/vim.\n\nRequires an active connection. Saving overwrites the file on the server, so double-check important config files first.",

  "helpAiTitle": "AI assistant — chat & run commands",
  "helpAiBody": "Ask an AI assistant about your server and let it suggest commands you can run with one tap.\n\nSet it up (once):\n1. Open Settings → AI.\n2. Choose a provider and get an API key:\n   • Claude (Anthropic) — console.anthropic.com → API keys\n   • ChatGPT (OpenAI) — platform.openai.com → API keys\n   • Gemini (Google) — aistudio.google.com → API key\n   • OpenAI-compatible (OpenRouter, Groq, local Ollama…) — paste the service's key and a Base URL ending in /v1.\n3. Optionally pick a model (defaults are filled in; tap a suggestion chip or type your own).\n4. Tap Save key.\n\nUsing it:\n• Type a question in your own language — the assistant replies in the same language.\n• When it proposes a shell command it puts it in a code block with a «Run» button. Tap Run and confirm; the command executes over SSH on the active server and the output is fed back into the chat.\n• Nothing runs automatically — you always confirm first, and destructive commands are flagged.\n\nCost & privacy: requests go directly from your device to the provider you chose, using your own API key (you pay the provider, per their pricing). The key is stored only in the Android Keystore. The assistant only sees what you type and any command output you choose to share.",

  "helpActionsTitle": "Quick actions — one-tap commands",
  "helpActionsBody": "Buttons that run a saved command on the active server with a single tap — for things you do often.\n\nBuilt-in actions cover common tasks: disk usage, listening ports, failed services, recent logins, public IP, available updates, top processes by RAM, update & upgrade, reboot, and more. Heavy ones (reboot, upgrade…) ask for confirmation first.\n\nAdd your own:\n1. Tap «Add action».\n2. Title — the button label.\n3. Command — any shell command or pipeline (e.g. systemctl restart nginx).\n4. Folder — optional grouping.\n5. «Confirm before running» — turn on for heavy or destructive commands (rm, restart, reboot…).\n6. Save.\n\nCustom actions can be edited or deleted later; built-in ones cannot be changed. After an action runs you see its result and exit code (exit 0 = success). Actions need an active connection. Use the search box to find an action in a long list.",

  "helpSecurityTitle": "Security & privacy",
  "helpSecurityBody": "How VPS Admin protects your data:\n\n• Secrets stay on the device. SSH passwords, private keys, key passphrases and AI API keys are stored only in the Android Keystore via flutter_secure_storage (hardware-backed on most devices). They are never written to plain settings, never put into backups as plaintext, and never sent anywhere except to your server (for SSH) or the AI provider you chose (for the API key).\n\n• Nothing leaves your phone uninvited. No account, no cloud sync, no telemetry. Server lists and settings live locally on the device.\n\n• App lock. In Settings → Security enable «Lock on launch» to require biometric (fingerprint/face) or device PIN every time the app opens. If biometrics fail or aren't set up, the app stays accessible so a sensor error can't lock you out.\n\n• Open-source core. The free core is public, so the security-relevant code can be inspected.\n\nGood practice: prefer SSH keys over passwords, put a passphrase on your key, and turn on App lock if your device is shared.",

  "helpUpdatesTitle": "Updates",
  "helpUpdatesBody": "New versions are published as APKs on the project's GitHub Releases page, and the app can check for them itself.\n\nSettings → Updates:\n• Off — never check.\n• Notify — check on launch and tell you when a newer version exists.\n• Auto — check on launch and, if there's an update, download it and open the installer automatically.\n• Check now — check immediately, whatever the mode.\n\nHow it works: the app reads the latest release tag on GitHub (e.g. v1.0.7), compares it with the installed version, and if it's newer offers to download the APK. Installing always goes through Android's own installer, which asks for your confirmation — the app can't install silently. The first time, you may need to allow «Install unknown apps» for VPS Admin.\n\nIf «Check now» says you're up to date but you expected something newer, the release may not be published yet, or its tag/version wasn't bumped."
}
